## The Business Analyst role across the ADLC

As a BA with dbt, you participate in every stage:

| Stage | Your role as BA |
|-------|----------------|
| PLAN | Define what data the business needs and why |
| DEVELOP | Write SQL models that transform raw data |
| TEST | Validate data matches business expectations |
| DEPLOY | Schedule automated runs in dbt Cloud |
| ANALYZE | Build Power BI dashboards on clean data |
| DISCOVER | Identify new optimization opportunities |
| OBSERVE | Monitor KPIs and data freshness |
| OPERATE | Maintain and improve existing pipelines |

---

## Why the ADLC matters for your career

Traditional Business Analyst:
- Receives data → analyzes → presents → done

ADLC-aware Business Analyst (top 1%):
- Owns the entire data lifecycle
- Guarantees data quality at every stage
- Connects business needs with technical implementation
- Monitors and improves continuously

---

## Key concepts introduced in this module

**DAG (Directed Acyclic Graph)**
The visual map of how your dbt models depend on each other.

source → staging → intermediate → final model

**Data lineage**
The ability to trace exactly where each number in your 
dashboard comes from — critical for data trust.

**CI/CD for data**
Continuous Integration / Continuous Deployment applied to 
data pipelines — dbt enables automated testing before 
any change goes to production.

---

## Key takeaway

The ADLC transforms Business Analysts from report builders 
into data engineers who own the full pipeline — from raw 
data to business decision.

This is the mindset shift that separates the top 1%.

